Table I, Table II and Table III summarize the performance of FedAvg, DP-FedAvg and Fed-SMP after T𝑇T rounds on Fashion-MNIST, SVHN and Shakespeare, respectively.
We run each experiment with 5 random seeds and report the average and standard deviation of testing accuracy. Note that we always report the best testing accuracy across all rounds in each experiment. We also report the uplink communication cost that denotes the size of the data sent from a client to the server as the input into the secure aggregation protocol, which equals to 32​k×T×(r/n)32𝑘𝑇𝑟𝑛32k\times T\times(r/n) bits for Fed-SMP and 32​d×T×(r/n)32𝑑𝑇𝑟𝑛32d\times T\times(r/n) bits for DP-FedAvg and FedAvg. The privacy for DP-FedAvg and Fed-SMP is the accumulated privacy loss ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon at the end of the training.

From Table I, we can see that the non-private FedAvg achieves a testing accuracy of 86.61%percent86.6186.61\% on Fashion-MNIST dataset. When adding Gaussian noise to ensure (1.01,n−1.1)1.01superscript𝑛1.1(1.01,n^{-1.1})-DP, the accuracy drops to 71.40%percent71.4071.40\% for DP-FedAvg. By choosing a proper value of p𝑝p, Fed-SMP can reach a higher accuracy than DP-FedAvg under the same level of DP guarantee. For example, the highest testing accuracy of Fed-SMP-topksubscripttop𝑘\operatorname{top}_{k} is 80.76%percent80.7680.76\% when p=0.005𝑝0.005p=0.005, outperforming DP-FedAvg by 11%percent1111\%; the highest testing accuracy of Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrand𝑘\operatorname{rand}_{k} is 79.88%percent79.8879.88\% when p=0.4𝑝0.4p=0.4, outperforming DP-FedAvg by 10%percent1010\%.

For the communication cost, we can observe from Table I-III that the uplink communication cost for Fed-SMP on both datasets is relatively lower than that of DP-FedAvg and FedAvg under the same privacy guarantee, since our scheme integrates well with the secure aggregation protocol and takes advantage of model update compression. To further demonstrate the communication efficiency of Fed-SMP, we show the convergence speed and communication cost of our Fed-SMP algorithms. Specifically, we select the Fed-SMP algorithms with the optimal compression ratio and show its testing accuracy with respect to the communication round and uplink communication cost in Fig. 2, compared with DP-FedAvg and FedAvg: For Fashion-MNIST dataset, we draw the results of Fed-SMP-topksubscripttop𝑘\operatorname{top}_{k} with p=0.005𝑝0.005p=0.005 and Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrand𝑘\operatorname{rand}_{k} with p=0.4𝑝0.4p=0.4, while achieving (1.01,n−1.1)1.01superscript𝑛1.1(1.01,n^{-1.1})-DP; for SVHN dataset, we draw the results of Fed-SMP-topksubscripttop𝑘\operatorname{top}_{k} with p=0.01𝑝0.01p=0.01 and Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrand𝑘\operatorname{rand}_{k} with p=0.4𝑝0.4p=0.4, while achieving (1.01,n−1.1)1.01superscript𝑛1.1(1.01,n^{-1.1})-DP; for Shakespeare dataset, we draw the results of Fed-SMP-topksubscripttop𝑘\operatorname{top}_{k} with p=0.05𝑝0.05p=0.05 and Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrand𝑘\operatorname{rand}_{k} with p=0.2𝑝0.2p=0.2, while achieving (6.99,n−1.1)6.99superscript𝑛1.1(6.99,n^{-1.1})-DP.

From Table I-Table III, we have observed that as compression ratio p𝑝p decreases from 1.0 to a small value (e.g., 0.005), the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP first increases and then decreases. This is due to the change of privacy error and compression error in the convergence bound (7), which is controlled by k𝑘k. Since the compression ratio p=k/d𝑝𝑘𝑑p=k/d, the smaller p𝑝p is, the lower the privacy error is, but the compression error could increase. In the following, we conduct additional experiments to further demonstrate this tradeoff under various compression ratios. As it is hard to directly show the tradeoff between privacy error and compression error, we study the difference between the performances of Fed-SMP and FedAvg-randksubscriptrand𝑘\operatorname{rand}_{k}/topksubscripttop𝑘\operatorname{top}_{k}, which differ only in DP noise addition.

references: In this part, we study the tradeoff between privacy and model accuracy of Fed-SMP. In Table IV-VII, we show the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP with respect to the privacy loss, under different compression ratios. Note that here we vary the noise multiplier σ𝜎\sigma to achieve different privacy losses. We can see that under the same compression ratio p𝑝p, the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP always decreases when the privacy loss ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon decreases. For example, the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrand𝑘\operatorname{rand}_{k} with p=0.005𝑝0.005p=0.005 decreases from 60.02%percent60.0260.02\% to 51.72%percent51.7251.72\% on Fashion-MNIST dataset when the privacy loss ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon decreases from 2.02 to 0.44. The reason is that as ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon decreases, the noise multiplier σ𝜎\sigma increases (according to Theorem 1), and hence, the convergence error increases (according to Theorem 2). Furthermore, we also observe that under the same privacy loss, the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP always increases at first and then decreases, as the compression ratio p𝑝p increases. For example, when the privacy loss ϵ=2.02italic-ϵ2.02\epsilon=2.02, the testing accuracy of Fed-SMP-randksubscriptrand𝑘\operatorname{rand}_{k} on SVHN dataset increases from 28.18%percent28.1828.18\% to 81.35%percent81.3581.35\% and then decreases to 80.39%percent80.3980.39\%, as the compression ratio p𝑝p increases from 0.05 to 0.8. This matches with our observations from Fig. 3, i.e., there exists an optimal compression ratio that achieves the highest testing accuracy under the same privacy loss (as highlighted in the table) due to the tradeoff between privacy and compression errors.

Besides, the optimal compression ratio decreases as the privacy loss decreases. For example, from Table IX, the optimal p𝑝p for Fed-SMP-topksubscripttop𝑘\operatorname{top}_{k} on Shakespeare dataset is 0.1 when ϵ=11.51italic-ϵ11.51\epsilon=11.51, and as ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon decreases to 3.39, the optimal p𝑝p decreases to 0.01. We observe similar trends on Table IV-VIII. It is because that the optimal p𝑝p always balances the tradeoff between privacy and compression errors to minimize the overall convergence error. As ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon decreases, the noise multiplier σ𝜎\sigma increases, and thus, the privacy error increases. In this case, the optimal p𝑝p should decrease to reduce the privacy error.
